A-L-B-R-O.

This is the book conservation section of the Conservation Division, and as the name would imply, it is where we deal with the conservation treatment of bound rare materials.

Well, this is the rare book conservation section.
There are three sections in terms of specialties in the offices.

We have rare book conservation, we have art on paper conservation, and we have a concept of conservation called phased conservation, which essentially is stabilization as opposed to actual one-on-one treatment.

What you see here primarily is an individual item selected from the collection through a process of negotiation between the conservator and the curator based on its importance to the library and based on its
condition.
Theoretically, most valuable, worst condition is where we start and then work our way down through the 117 million authors.
Who makes the decision of importance?
That would be a curatorial decision.
And it's very subjective.
And you can't really argue with it.
I mean, a person in the geography and math division is going to have a different notion of what constitutes importance as a person who works in the music division.

Periodically, there are attempts on the part of management to sort of put down a set of guidelines which would be standard to the library for selection, but it's normally Shoup shouted down pretty quickly because it just is not a very sensible objective.
In any case, we then work with each curator and work out every year a proposal which we give to that division which assigns our points or hours broken down
based on a contract which says this is what we're going to do for you in these three areas of specialty book paper and phase so this is all figured out
If this is all determined, well, in advance, you don't get any, there's no triage here.

Sometimes material will be accessioned, which is too badly damaged or in such a condition that it can't be catalogued, and we would have to fix it then.
There are four main processes by which work comes down here.
We have a series of ongoing projects that have gone on for years.
The Jefferson Collection, naturally.
The Rosenwald Collection, the Cabinet of American Illustration, the Moldenauer Music Management Collection.
Huge collections of very, very important materials, which we work bit by bit on an ongoing process.
We have materials that are accessioned, as I said, and need to be worked on right away.
We have exhibit issues, where we have an exhibit like the American Treasure Show,
Things have to go on exhibit looking a certain way.

Well, that's the theory.
The practice not always is that way.
The curators often are making up their minds about what's going to go into the show two weeks before the show opens.
And the fourth way is that we need to work on a certain set of things all the time.
In order for the skills that we have to be maintained,
You can't work on a certain type of binding once every five years.
You've got to do it all the time.
Or you're not doing justice to the craft aspect of the work, as opposed to just kind of, you know, thundering through something the same as done.

Right.

and then reallocated to another album in a different order.
